{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658531","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658531"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:49:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:49:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20767"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20767","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20767"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13642"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95750"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13642","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13642"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20767"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78551"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11582"},{"type":"tags","id":"11751"},{"type":"tags","id":"12621"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32805"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32806"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95750","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/95750"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents with abnormal uterine bleeding. Endometrial biopsy reveals an increased number of endometrial glands with architectural complexity but no cytologic atypia.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the underlying pathophysiology of endometrial hyperplasia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Metaplastic transformation of endometrial stromal cells","Accumulation of irreversible genetic alterations","Excessive progesterone receptor activation","Unopposed estrogen stimulation","Primary dysfunction of endometrial stem cells"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe pathophysiology of endometrial hyperplasia primarily involves \u003Cstrong\u003Eunopposed estrogen stimulation\u003C/strong\u003E. In the normal menstrual cycle, endometrial proliferation is stimulated by estrogen and limited by progesterone. When this hormonal balance is disturbed with either absolute or relative increases in estrogen without adequate progesterone counterbalance, excessive proliferation of endometrial glands occurs, resulting in hyperplasia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetaplastic transformation of endometrial stromal cells\u003C/strong\u003E - Endometrial hyperplasia involves proliferation of glandular epithelial cells, not metaplastic changes in stromal cells.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAccumulation of irreversible genetic alterations\u003C/strong\u003E - While genetic alterations may develop in hyperplastic tissue and potentially lead to cancer, endometrial hyperplasia is initially a reversible process that can regress if the hormonal imbalance is corrected.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExcessive progesterone receptor activation\u003C/strong\u003E - Progesterone actually inhibits endometrial proliferation. Increased progesterone would counteract hyperplasia rather than cause it.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrimary dysfunction of endometrial stem cells\u003C/strong\u003E - Endometrial hyperplasia is primarily driven by hormonal imbalance affecting differentiated cells, not by intrinsic stem cell dysfunction.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEndometrial hyperplasia represents a risk factor for subsequent development of endometrial carcinoma. The increased cell division associated with hyperplasia elevates the risk of acquiring genetic aberrations that may eventually drive malignant transformation, particularly in cases with cytologic atypia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Hyperplasia is a reversible increase in cell number that occurs in response to specific stimuli and often accompanies hypertrophy.","Endometrial hyperplasia typically results from unopposed estrogen stimulation without adequate progesterone counterbalance.","Pathologic hyperplasia increases cancer risk due to increased cell proliferation and potential for acquiring genetic mutations."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 2; page 59."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78551"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20767"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78551","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/78551"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-29T12:25:47+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-29T12:26:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13642"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95750"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11582","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11582"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Cell injury, cell death and adaptations","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":1,"createdAt":"2025-02-26T15:12:31+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-26T15:12:31+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"18"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11751"